Student class schedules for the 20-21 academic year are now available to be viewed in Infinite Campus.

In order to ensure balanced class sizes that meet social distancing requirements the division of students into cohorts will not be finalized until Thursday, 9/10. This will allow for the two cohorts to reflect student schedule changes that are made this upcoming week as students review their class schedules. Students that selected the hybrid instructional model will receive their cohort assignment by the end of the day on Thursday, 9/10.

The first day of school for students is now, Monday, September 14, 2020. The delay to the start of school is to provide additional time to prepare the facility and technology for students, faculty, and staff based on recent guidance from the New Jersey Department of Health and Executive Order 175.

Additional changes are listed below.

November

June
Tuesday, June 22 ‚Äì Graduation / Last day for Students and Teachers

post_text:
Parents and Guardians of Linwood, Northfield and Somers Point

It has been brought to the Mainland Regional High School District's attention that P-EBT cards have been sent out by the State of New Jersey in error. At this time we are still investigating. We are in contact with the State and it appears there was a file error upon transmittal by a third party. If you are a parent/guardian that is not eligible for P-EBT assistance the card should be mailed back to the address listed on the back of the card. You may also drop the card off at the High School and we will mail the cards back to the State of New Jersey. Mainland's business hours are Monday-Thursday 8:00 AM to 2:00 PM. If you have any questions, please contact the Mainland Regional High School Business Office at 609-927-8058. We apologize for any inconvience.

The MRHS 2020 Yearbook has arrived.

Yearbooks purchased by Seniors will be delivered by the MRHS "Street Team" on Wednesday, June 17, 2020.

Yearbooks purchased by underclassmen can be picked up on Thursday, June 18, 2020 from 9:00 AM to 11:15 AM. In order to comply with social distancing guidelines, please adhere to the following schedule.

Juniors from 9:00 AM to 9:45 AM
Sophomores from 9:45 AM to 10:30AM
Freshmen from 10:30 AM to 11:15 AM

When picking up your yearbook, please come to the main entrance on Oak Avenue. Please follow social distancing protocols and be sure to wear a mask. A limited supply of yearbooks are available and can be purchased on Thursday, June 18, 2020 for $100 (CASH ONLY).

Please contact Mr. Jim O'Kane at jokane@mainlandregional.net or Mrs. Rebeca McDevitt at rmcdevitt@mainlandregional.net with additional questions or concerns.

post_text: Every day, but especially throughout June each year, MRHS celebrates our Mustangs in the LGBTQ community! Pride Month is the promotion of the self-affirmation, dignity, equality, and increased visibility of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) people as a social group. June is the month chosen to celebrate Pride as it was the month of the Stonewall riots, the protests that changed gay rights for a lot of people in America and beyond. It's about people coming together in love and friendship, to show how far gay rights have come, even if in some places there's still some work to be done. Pride Month is about teaching tolerance, education in pride history and continuing to move forward in equality. It calls for people to remember how damaging homophobia was and still can be. It's all about being proud of who you are no matter who you love.

June is the month chosen to celebrate Pride as it was the month of the Stonewall riots, the protests that changed gay rights for a lot of people in America and beyond. It's about people coming together in love and friendship, to show how far gay rights have come, even if in some places there's still some work to be done. Greetings Class of 2020!!
Get ready cause the MRHS "Street Team" is headed your way! On Wednesday June 17, 2020, Mainland teachers and staff will be delivering Mainland Swag, including yard signs, in honor of the Class of 2020! We will be stopping by your homes in Linwood, Somers Point and Northfield between the hours of 1:00 PM and 3:00 PM. Choice students and those living in surrounding towns will see delivery sometime after 9:00 AM. If you are not home, you can stop by the High School that afternoon from 3:00 PM to 5:00 PM or Thursday June 18, 2020 from 10:00 AM to12:00 PM to pick up your swag! Congratulations Class of 2020 & GO MUSTANGS!

Good morning all!

Memorial Day is always a special day of year to think and remember those who gave up everything for what we have. While this isn‚Äôt the Memorial Day that we all thought we were going to have this year, we still wanted to do our part. Normally, at this time, we would be getting ready to parade around town, but with the conditions as they are, we came up with a different idea.

Performing our parade tune Battle Hymn, the Mainland Regional VIRTUAL Marching Band! This is dedicated to all those who have given the ultimate sacrifice. Happy Memorial Day!

https://youtu.be/uT29GytoVPM

Jon Ratcliffe
Marching Band Director
Mainland Regional High School

post_text:
Please review attached announcement regarding Virtual Graduation Ceremonies.

Mainland Regional High School is currently in the process of planning a virtual graduation ceremony as well as other creative ways to recognize our 2020 graduates. Additional information will be forthcoming in the near future. We are excited to celebrate our graduates, but an in-person ceremony that brings families and graduates to the Mustang Corral (football stadium) is not permissible at this time. Even though, we can not currently gather at the High School to celebrate our graduates, we plan to hold an in-person celebration in the upcoming months or in the fall, once we are permitted.

Thank you & GO MUSTANGS!

post_text:
LET‚ÄôS CELEBRATE ASIAN AMERICAN AND PACIFIC ISLANDER HERITAGE MONTH!

The MRHS Asian Cultural Club wants to make you aware that the month of May is Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage month. It celebrates the culture, traditions, and history of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders in the United States.

The club decided to post a "fun fact" every Friday in May about Asian cultures as a way for us to celebrate this month. We have also created our own Instagram @mrhs_asianculture, and would love for you to join. We will be posting our weekly fun facts as well as creating videos of the members making traditional Asian recipes as well as sharing their history of their cultures, etc.

Below is the "fun fact" that was posted on Friday, May 1st. I hope everyone is staying healthy and happy in these uncertain times.

The Mainland Regional High School Board of Education's 2020-2021 Public Budget Hearing will be on Thursday, April 30, 2020 beginning at 5:30 PM and will be held virtually online. Members of the public that want to view the meeting and/or participate in the Public Comment portion of the meeting, can go to the District‚Äôs website www.mainlandregional.net on Thursday, April 30, 2020 beginning at 5:00 PM for directions on how to access the Board meeting. We will not be hosting the Board of Education meeting during this current health crisis in the High School‚Äôs library because the facility is closed.

To be clear, access to the virtual online Board of Education meeting will be posted on the District‚Äôs website at 5:00 PM on Thursday, April 30, 2020.

Thank you & GO MUSTANGS!

post_text:
Dear Parents & Guardians,

Has your employment/income changed due to this current health crisis?

Mainland Regional High School is committed to ensuring that all of our students, regardless of the economic conditions in our geographic area, are provided with all necessary resources to succeed. We are also committed to ensuring that each student is able to fully participate in Mainland‚Äôs extracurricular activities regardless of economic status. Mainland encourages all families that are eligible to apply for participation in the federal free and reduced lunch program. Participation in this program not only provides your student with a free or reduced cost breakfast and lunch, but also determines their eligibility for SAT, ACT, AP and college application fee waivers.

Please review the attached Economic Toolkit that the District has developed for students and families.

Mark C. Marrone
Chief School Administrator

post_text:
Spring Musical 2nd Postponement

At this time, the Mainland Regional High School District is postponing the Spring Musical ‚ÄúMamma Mia‚Äù until a later date to be determined based on local, state, and federal guidance/recommendations regarding responding to this current health crisis. The District is choosing to postpone the Spring Musical as opposed to cancelling it, in hopes of providing students an opportunity to perform at a later date. Unfortunately, we are unable to provide that date at this time and the musical‚Äôs postponement may change based on future guidance and recommendations. In addition, please understand that we are unable to guarantee that this second postponement will not eventually result in a cancellation or modified performance. We understand your disappointment and know that we are working to develop solutions to issues that directly impact our students during this unprecedented time.

Mark C. Marrone
Chief School Administrator

post_text: Attention Rowers...
shared_text:
Southern New Jersey Scholastic Rowing Association
March 13 at 8:29 PM ¬∑

Good Evening Coaches and Parents:

Southern New Jersey scholastic Rowing Association remains committed to providing an opportunity fro our high school athletes to compete in a safe and fair environment. As of this afternoon there have been numerous schools that have seized all sports programs indefinitely along with Flicks 1-4 being cancelled. With that being said we are cancelling the 1st 2 Sprints, March 21 and March 28, and optimistically scheduling the 3rd sprint for April 4th. We will closely monitor the situation with all of the local school districts and County Representatives to see if the County Championships will be feasible.
We will provide timely updated of any significant changes to these plans.
Thank you for your patience during this trying time.

Thank you

shared_text:
Glory Days Magazine
March 6 at 7:42 PM ¬∑

Heck of a day for Mainland senior Kylee Watson. This afternoon she was named the Gatorade Player of the Year in New Jersey, then prior to the South Jersey Group 3 semifinals against Absegami she was honored for becoming the school's first girls basketball player with 1,000 rebounds, and also received an award from GThing Basketball, being named "Miss NJ" in girls basketball. Then she went out and led all scorers with 17 points in a 41-12 Mustangs victory while also scoring the 2,000th point of her career! (Glory Days photo/Dave O'Sullivan)

post_text: Welcome to another International Food Day this year at MRHS! Chef Ilene and her crew have teamed up with our Upstanders to make sharing culture through food a regular part of the lunch experience. Each month, on the 1st and 3rd Thursdays, there will be a line in the cafeteria dedicated to a different region in the world. Today: Soul Food! Fried Chicken, Mac-n-cheese, Candied Yams, Collard Greens, Corn Bread, and Cake. Also, the Upstanders would like to hear from you! If you would like to have food from your region of origin included on a future International Food Day, please reach out to Dr. Spagone in the Guidance Office. Enjoy!

The Mainland Regional boys and girls swimming teams both advanced today to the South Jersey Public B championship meets, winning their semifinal matchups against Shawnee and Clearview, respectively. The boys beat the Renegades 93-77 while the girls raced past the Pioneers 108-62 to earn a berth in the sectional final for the first time in seven years. There was also a bit of other interesting news to come out of that meet. We'll have more for you tonight at glorydaysonline.com, so stay tuned! (Glory Days photo/Dave O'Sullivan)
